[[Image:Acerra.jpg|right|250px|thumb|Acerra.]]
In [[Ancient Roman]] [[sacrifice|sacrificial]] tradition, an '''acerra''' ([[Greek language|Greek]]: ''{{lang|grc|λιβανωτρίς}}'') was the [[incense]] box used in sacrifices. The incense was taken out of the acerra and let fall upon the burning [[altar]]; hence, we have the expression ''de acerra libare''. ([[turibulum]])
The acerra was also, according to [[Sextus Pompeius Festus|Festus]], a small altar, placed before the dead, on which perfumes were burnt. There was a law in the [[Twelve Tables]], which restricted the use of acerrae at [[funeral]]s.
